Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 AM, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his squad. Silently stepping out of his bed, he put on his combat uniform, fastened his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pockets, he quietly stepped out of the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He took out a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. Lighting it, he took a small puff before gently opening the door. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm, as half the time it didn't work, since all that came out of the speakers was a faint hiss.
"Are you waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching on foot.
"Ouep", répondit Cohren.
"Qu'avez-vous prévu d'utiliser cette fois-ci ?"
Avant qu'il ne puisse répondre, la porte s'ouvrit et Harris, Craith et d'autres soldats se dépêchèrent de sortir, déjà habillés et équipés.
"Bonjour", dit Craith.
"Qu'est-ce qui vous a réveillés ?", demanda Cohren.
"Well, primo, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up with today. Secundo, the first shock troops on their feet are the first for breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He reached out and activated a switch. An alarm rang inside the barracks, loud and piercing. He heard a commotion inside and some agitation.
"Damn it, Valturi," shouted Nemic. "We could have thought they would have learned to get up at the same time as you, by now."
"Well, my buddies from the training camp here did it," Cohren turned towards Harris, Craith and Ravik. "But once again, their squad and section leaders know how to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company exited en masse. All had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Good morning everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"Except your respect, sir, why do you persist in waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are terrible. And because Daybreak doesn't do lazy mornings," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you all have your personal effects," he continued. As first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We're not coming back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to complete final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
The members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. At first, they were split into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a broken company and Cohren didn't know what to think of his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly for reasons that had motivated him.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first squad, walked together under the light of the numerous lights of the forward operating base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had used Wild Weasel assaults, both in the air and on the ground, to fight them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," began Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are we sending them?"
"An advanced operational base outside of Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," replied Cohren as he took a drag on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to smoking, but a year of combat changes a man, and he said nothing.
"Damn it. The situation is deteriorating on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from this place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send aid to the Kurgan front.' Why not send aid to the Howland front?"
"Amen, my brother," said Cohren as he flicked his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're going with the first armored squad, so we won't have to march. Captain Shaw should be here."
"Shaw got us a transport?", asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Yeah. Honestly, it's not as bad as I thought. I mean, it's not exceptional, but it's not unbearable."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "All units of the Exodus company, report to the western vehicle yard when you're done. We're departing with the first armored squad at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking officers when they arrived here. All four had been very good friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed to go back so long, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were then squad leaders. But Craith now commanded the second squad since a week ago, after the previous commander was discharged due to being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked toward the vehicle yard, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busy, ensuring their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the armored squad commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol case before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
